0.body:
[Note that this is a very early version and actively being worked on; thanks for your patience] PRQL is a modern language for transforming data — a simpler and more powerful SQL. Like SQL, it's readable, explicit and declarative. Unlike SQL, it forms a logical pipeline of transformations, and supports abstractions such as variables and functions. It can be used with any database that uses SQL, since it transpiles to SQL. Let's get started with an example: PRQLSQL from employees
filter country_code = "USA" # Each line transforms the previous result.
derive [ # This adds columns / variables. gross_salary: salary + payroll_tax, gross_cost: gross_salary + benefits_cost # Variables can use other variables.
]
filter gross_cost > 0
group [title, country_code] ( # For each group use a nested pipeline aggregate [ # Aggregate each group to a single row average salary, average gross_salary, sum salary, sum gross_salary, average gross_cost, sum_gross_cost: sum gross_cost, ct: count, ]
)
sort sum_gross_cost
filter ct > 200
take 20
join countries side:left [country_code]
derive [ always_true: true, db_version: s"version()", # An S-string, which transpiles directly into SQL
] WITH table_0 AS ( SELECT title, country_code, AVG(salary), AVG(salary + payroll_tax), SUM(salary), SUM(salary + payroll_tax), AVG(salary + payroll_tax + benefits_cost), SUM(salary + payroll_tax + benefits_cost) AS sum_gross_cost, COUNT(*) AS ct FROM employees WHERE country_code = 'USA' AND salary + payroll_tax + benefits_cost > 0 GROUP BY title, country_code HAVING COUNT(*) > 200 ORDER BY sum_gross_cost LIMIT 20
)
SELECT table_0.*, countries.*, country_code, countries.true AS always_true, version() AS db_version
FROM table_0 LEFT JOIN countries USING(country_code) As you can see, PRQL is a linear pipeline of transformations — each line of the query is a transformation of the previous line's result. You can see that in SQL, operations do not follow one another, which makes it hard to compose larger queries.
0.title: Introduction

1.body: PRQL queries are structured differently to SQL queries — they represent a pipeline of transformations, each one changing the previous result into a new result. Pipelines [TODO]
1.title: Queries

11.body:
Intervals are represented by {N}{periods}, such as 2years or 10minutes, without a space. These aren't the same as ISO8601, because we evaluated P3Y6M4DT12H30M5S to be difficult to understand, but we could support a simplified form if there's demand for it. We don't currently support compound expressions, for example 2years10months, but most DBs will allow 2years + 10months. Please raise an issue if this is inconvenient. PRQLSQL from projects
derive first_check_in: start + 10days SELECT projects.*, start + INTERVAL '10' DAY AS first_check_in
FROM projects
11.title: Intervals

12.body: Core principle of the language is a pipeline, which is a series of sequential transformations of a table (or data frame). There is only a few different types of transformations:
12.title: Transforms

13.body:
specifies a data source from {table reference} Example: PRQLSQL from employees SELECT employees.*
FROM employees
13.title: From

14.body:
picks columns based on their names select [{expression}] Example: PRQLSQL from employees
select [first_name, last_name] SELECT first_name, last_name
FROM employees
14.title: Select

15.body:
adds new columns that are computed from existing columns derive [{new_name}: {expression}] Example: PRQLSQL from employees
derive gross_salary: salary + payroll_tax SELECT employees.*, salary + payroll_tax AS gross_salary
FROM employees PRQLSQL from employees
derive [ gross_salary: salary + payroll_tax, gross_cost: gross_salary + benefits_cost
] SELECT employees.*, salary + payroll_tax AS gross_salary, salary + payroll_tax + benefits_cost AS gross_cost
FROM employees
15.title: Derive

16.body:
picks rows based on their values filter {boolean expression} Example: from employees
filter (length last_name < 3)
16.title: Filter

17.body:
picks first n rows take {n} Example: PRQLSQL from employees
take 10 SELECT employees.*
FROM employees
LIMIT 10
17.title: Take

18.body:
orders the rows by the values of selected columns sort {column} Arguments: a column identifier of the key to sort by Example: PRQLSQL from employees
sort age SELECT employees.*
FROM employees
ORDER BY age
18.title: Sort

19.body:
adds columns from another table, matching rows based on a condition join side:{inner|left|right|full} {table} {[conditions]} Arguments: side decides which rows to include. Defaults to inner table reference list of conditions If all terms are column identifiers, this will compile to USING(...). In this case, both of the tables must have specified column. The result will only contain one column instead one for each table. Example: PRQLSQL from employees
join side:left positions [id=employee_id] SELECT employees.*, positions.*
FROM employees LEFT JOIN positions ON id = employee_id Example: PRQLSQL from employees
join side:full positions [emp_no] SELECT employees.*, positions.*, emp_no
FROM employees FULL JOIN positions USING(emp_no)
19.title: Join

20.body:
A group transform maps a pipeline over a number of groups. The groups are determined by the columns passed to group's first argument. The most conventional use of group is with aggregate: PRQLSQL from employees
group [title, country] ( aggregate [ average salary, ct: count ]
) SELECT title, country, AVG(salary), COUNT(*) AS ct
FROM employees
GROUP BY title, country In concept, a transform in context of a group does the same transformation to the group as it would to the table — for example finding the employee who joined first: PRQLSQL from employees
sort join_date
take 1 SELECT employees.*
FROM employees
ORDER BY join_date
LIMIT 1 To find the employee who joined first in each department, it's exactly the same pipeline, but within a group expression: Not yet implemented, ref https://github.com/prql/prql/issues/421 from employees
group role ( sort join_date # taken from above take 1
)
20.title: Group

21.body:
group rows by one or more columns aggregate [{expression or assign operations}] Example: PRQLSQL from employees
aggregate [ average salary, ct: count
] SELECT AVG(salary), COUNT(*) AS ct
FROM employees
21.title: Aggregate

23.body:
Most keywords that take a single argument can also take a list, so these are equivalent: from employees
-select salary
+select [salary] More examples in list-equivalence.md .
23.title: Lists

24.body:
A line-break generally creates a pipelined transformation. For example: PRQLSQL from tbl SELECT tbl.*
FROM tbl col1, col2,
\]
filter col1 = col2
```` ...is equivalent to: PRQLSQL from tbl | select [col1, col2] | filter col1 = col2 SELECT col1, col2
FROM tbl
WHERE col1 = col2 A line-break doesn't created a pipeline in a few cases: Within a list (e.g. the select example above). When the following line is a new statement, by starting with a keyword such as func.
24.title: Pipelines

25.body: See CTE Example . This is no longer point-free, but that's a feature rather than a requirement. The alternative is subqueries, which are fine at small scale, but become difficult to digest as complexity increases.
25.title: CTEs

26.body:
Functions are a fundamental abstraction in PRQL — they allow us to run code in many places that we've written once. This reduces the number of errors in our code, makes our code more readable, and simplifies making changes. Functions have two types of parameters: Positional parameters, which require an argument. Named parameters, which optionally take an argument, otherwise using their default value. So this function is named celsius_of_fahrenheit and has one parameter temp: PRQLSQL func celsius_of_fahrenheit temp = (temp - 32) * 3 from cities
derive temp_c: (celsius_of_fahrenheit temp_f) SELECT cities.*, temp_f - 32 * 3 AS temp_c
FROM cities This function named interp, and has two positional parameters named higher and x, and one named parameter named lower which takes a default argument of 0. It calculates the proportion of the distance that x is between lower and higher. PRQLSQL func interp lower:0 higher x = (x - lower) / (higher - lower) from students
derive [ sat_proportion_1: (interp 1600 sat_score), sat_proportion_2: (interp lower:0 1600 sat_score),
] SELECT students.*, sat_score - 0 / 1600 - 0 AS sat_proportion_1, sat_score - 0 / 1600 - 0 AS sat_proportion_2
FROM students
26.title: Functions

27.body:
Consistent with the principles of PRQL, it's possible to pipe values into functions, which makes composing functions more readable. When piping a value into a function, the value is passed as an argument to the final positional parameter of the function. Here's the same result as the examples above with an alternative construction: PRQLSQL func interp lower:0 higher x = (x - lower) / (higher - lower) from students
derive [ sat_proportion_1: (sat_score | interp 1600), sat_proportion_2: (sat_score | interp lower:0 1600),
] SELECT students.*, sat_score - 0 / 1600 - 0 AS sat_proportion_1, sat_score - 0 / 1600 - 0 AS sat_proportion_2
FROM students and PRQLSQL func celsius_of_fahrenheit temp = (temp - 32) * 3 from cities
derive temp_c: (temp_f | celsius_of_fahrenheit) SELECT cities.*, temp_f - 32 * 3 AS temp_c
FROM cities We can combine a chain of functions, which makes logic more readable: PRQLSQL func celsius_of_fahrenheit temp = (temp - 32) * 3
func interp lower:0 higher x = (x - lower) / (higher - lower) from kettles
derive boiling_proportion: (temp_c | celsius_of_fahrenheit | interp 100) SELECT kettles.*, temp_c - 32 * 3 - 0 / 100 - 0 AS boiling_proportion
FROM kettles
27.title: Piping

28.body: Currently, functions require a binding to variables in scope; they can't late-bind to column names; so for example: func return price = (price - dividend) / price_yesterday ...isn't yet a valid function, and instead would needs to be: func return price dividend price_yesterday = (price - dividend) / (price_yesterday) (which makes functions in this case not useful)

The simplest pipeline is just: PRQLSQL from employees SELECT employees.*
FROM employees
3.title: The simplest pipeline

4.body:
We can add additional lines, each one transforms the result: PRQLSQL from employees
derive gross_salary: (salary + payroll_tax) SELECT employees.*, salary + payroll_tax AS gross_salary
FROM employees ...and so on: PRQLSQL from employees
derive gross_salary: (salary + payroll_tax)
sort gross_salary SELECT employees.*, salary + payroll_tax AS gross_salary
FROM employees
ORDER BY gross_salary
4.title: Adding transformations

5.body: PRQL improves on many of SQL's awkward language features:
5.title: Language Features

6.body: Strings in PRQL can use either single or double quotes: PRQLSQL derive x: "hello world" SELECT 'hello world' AS x PRQLSQL derive x: 'hello world' SELECT 'hello world' AS x To quote a string containing quotes, either use the "other" type of quote, or use three-or-more quotes, and close with the same number. PRQLSQL derive x: '"hello world"' SELECT '"hello world"' AS x PRQLSQL derive x: """I said "hello world"!""" SELECT 'I said "hello world"!' AS x Currently PRQL does not adjust escape characters during the compilation process. Currently PRQL allows multiline strings with either a single character or multiple character quotes. This may change for strings using a single character quote in future versions.
6.title: Strings

7.body:
f-strings are a readable approach to building new strings from existing strings. Currently PRQL supports this for concatenating strings: PRQLSQL from x
select full_name: f"{first} {last}" SELECT CONCAT(first, ' ', last) AS full_name
FROM x This can be much easier to read for longer strings, relative to the SQL approach: PRQLSQL from x
select url: f"http{tls}://www.{domain}.{tld}/{page}" SELECT CONCAT( 'http', tls, '://www.', domain, '.', tld, '/', page ) AS url
FROM x In the future, this may extend to other types of formatting, such as datetimes, numbers, and padding. If there's a feature that would be helpful, please post an issue .
7.title: F-Strings

8.body:
An s-string inserts SQL directly, as an escape hatch when there's something that PRQL doesn't yet implement. For example, there's no version() function in SQL that returns the Postgres version, so if we want to use that, we use an s-string: PRQLSQL derive db_version: s"version()" SELECT version() AS db_version We can embed columns in an s-string using braces. For example, PRQL's standard library defines the average function as: func average column = s"AVG({column})" So this compiles using the function: PRQLSQL from employees
aggregate [average salary] SELECT AVG(salary)
FROM employees For those who have used python, s-strings are similar to python f-strings, but the result is SQL, rather than a string literal — a python f-string would produce "average(salary)", with the quotes. S-strings in user code are intended as an escape-hatch for an unimplemented feature. If we often need s-strings to express something, that's a sign we should implement it in PRQL / PRQL's stdlib.
8.title: S-Strings

9.body:
PRQL has a concise range syntax start..end, which can be accessed with the in function: PRQLSQL from employees
filter (age | in 18..40) SELECT employees.*
FROM employees
WHERE age BETWEEN 18 AND 40 Like in SQL, ranges are inclusive.
9.title: Ranges
